title: For Sale:  RARE Colt Army Model 1909 .45 Revolver 45
postcontent: This is a rare and fine Colt US Model 1909 Revolver in .45 Long Colt (modified). Only about 19,000 of these were made and almost all of those went straight to the Philippines and few survived in any condition, let alone with as much original bluing as this one retains. The Model 1909 was an "emergency" attempt to provide a double action .45 caliber side arm to US Army forces in the Philippines to fight the Moros in the Southern Philippine islands. Prior to the Model 1909, the US Army standard sidearms were .38 caliber, which had very little effect on attacking fanatical Islamist Moros, who were often drugged up (See my other auctions for a Colt 1901 issued to the 7th Cavalry in the Philippines in .38). In response to a call from the field for a larger caliber weapon, the Army brought out old Model 1873 Revolvers in .45 Long Colt as a stop gap measure until the Model 1909 was fielded. This Model 1909 is serial number 42821 and it is all matching with the serial number on the frame, crane, cylinder release latch, both grips and butt. The Cylinder retains 90%+ of the original blue finish and has the "RAC" inspector mark on the rear cylinder face, which stands for Rinaldo A. Carr, who is the famous Colt inspector of the Model 1873 Models. Wear is generally on the front edges and to the rear of the cylinder between two chambers. The Barrel is marked "COLT D.A. 45" on the left side, on top it has the Colt Patent information and the bottom of the barrel is marked "UNITED STATES PROPERTY," and "RAC". Barrel is where the predominant wear is located on this revolver and it largely carries a pewter finish with original bluing at the rear 1/3rd of the barrel where it joins the frame. The bore is, however, very clean with strong rifling. The Frame has a very clear and sharp Rampant Colt on the left side. Right side of the Frame has the inspection initials of Rinaldo Carr ("RAC") as well as the Army acceptance stamp of "WGP," which stands for Major Walter G. Penfield, US Army, who inspected and approved Model 1909s from serial number 42,801 through 49,503. Frame retains 90%+ of the original high quality Colt blue finish. The Cylinder Latch has the last 4 matching numbers and has 95% of the original blue finish. The Butt is marked "US/ARMY/MODEL/1909/No/42/821" and has the lanyard loop. The original walnut grips are in excellent condition and both are inspector marked "RAC" on the bottom and both correctly have the serial number penciled on the inside of each grip. The front and back grip strap finish is starting to turn a plum brown and pewter color. This is a very rare Colt revolver with a unique history fighting the Moros in the Philippines and is in incredible condition given that service. This Colt is C&R eligible
